Model.Name: sldemo_fuelsys_original
Model.P:
This is a model of a fuel control system where Stateflow(R) is used to handle the fault management of the system. The system contains four separate sensors: a throttle sensor, a speed sensor, an oxygen sensor, and a pressure sensor. Each of these sensors is represented by a parallel state in Stateflow. Each parallel state contains two substates, a normal state and a failed state (the exception being the oxygen sensor, which also contains a warmup state).
If any of the sensor readings is outside an acceptable range, then a fault is registered in Stateflow, and the substate of the corresponding subsystem transitions to the failed state. If a subsystem recovers, it can transition back to the normal state. The number of failures in the system at any given time is represented in the Fail parallel state.
The last parallel state in the Stateflow chart is called Fueling_Mode. This state regulates the oxygen to fuel mixture ratio. If a failure is detected, then the oxygen to fuel ratio is increased. If multiple failures are detected, then the fuel system is disabled until there are no longer multiple failures in the system.

state.P: This state determines the validity of the exhaust gas oxygen sensor (EGO) data.
The EGO sensor must come up to temperature before its data is reliable.
Normal EGO sensor operation gives a reliable indication of excess oxygen in the exhaust gas, from which air/fuel mixture can be inferred.

transition.P: The value for sufficient warm up to operational temperature (nominally 4.8 seconds).
The failure condition is indicated by excessive output voltage.

state.P: This state assesses the validity of the manifold absolute pressure (MAP) sensor.
The manifold pressure sensor gives a reliable indication of absolute pressure (MAP).
The pressure sensor (manifold, or MAP) no longer produces reliable data.
This state determines the validity of the throttle sensor signal.
The throttle sensor gives a reliable indication of the angle of the throttle plate.
Signal levels indicate that the throttle sensor data is no longer valid.

transition.P: A failure is indicated by data which is outside the expected range, typically due to an open or short circuit.

state.P: This state infers the validity of the speed sensor data. A failure is indicated by the presence of manifold vacuum at zero speed.
The speed sensor data accurately represents the engine speed.
The engine speed data is no longer available.

transition.P: Loss of a reliable speed sensor signal will indicate zero speed. This is deemed invalid when the manifold vacuum indicates otherwise.

state.P: This state maintains a count of the number of sensors in failure mode.
This state represents any of the conditions in which more than one sensor is in failure mode.
Three of the engine sensors have failed.
All four of the engine sensors have failed.
Two of the engine sensors have failed.
One of the engine sensors has failed.
Zero failures; all sensors are operational.
This state interprets the other states in the chart to directly control the fueling mode.
The fuel is completely shut off while in this state.
The speed is dangerously high, so shut off the fuel.
Cut off system operation due to multiple sensor failures.
The fuel is actively controlled while in this state.
The sensors are all operational, but the oxygen (EGO) sensor is warming up. We'll target a stoichiometric ratio, nonetheless, but won't close the loop around exhaust gas oxygen.
All sensors are in correct operating modes, so effective closed-loop mixture control can be used.
This mode enriches the mixture, lowering the air/fuel ratio.
Continue uninterrupted engine operation, but with a richer mixture.
